## **Tactical frivolity can create a powerful counternarrative, but struggles to scale beyond Portland**

By MILES BARRY —mabarry@ucdavis.edu

In September 2025, President Trump described Portland, Oregon as “[war-ravaged](https://www.npr.org/2025/09/28/nx-s1-5555496/trump-wants-to-send-troops-to-war-ravaged-portland-city-officials-say-theres-no-need#:~:text=Trump%20wants%20to%20send%20troops,say%20there's%20no%20need%20:%20NPR&text=Weekend%20Edition%20Sunday-,Trump%20wants%20to%20send%20troops%20to%20'war%2Dravaged'%20Portland,Officials%20there%20say%20it's%20unnecessary.),” citing daily protests outside of its United States Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) facility. 

When Trump’s secretary of homeland security, Kristi Noem, visited the city, she was met with a different sight. A video posted on Oct. 7 shows her staring down onto the street from the ICE facility rooftop, flanked by camo-wearing, burly, stone-faced men. Conservative influencer Benny Johnson accompanied Noem on the roof and claimed that she was staring down an “[army of Antifa](https://x.com/bennyjohnson/status/1975662466874175498)”. The “army” in question turned out to be mostly photojournalists, and a [man wearing a chicken suit](https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/kristi-noem-portland-visit-antifa-chicken-b2841736.html). 

As Portlanders mobilize against Trump’s deployment of federal agents in their city, costumes have come into vogue — especially inflatable frog suits. A growing movement titled the “[Portland Frog Brigades](https://www.kgw.com/article/news/local/the-story/portland-ice-protest-inflatable-frog-costume-symbol-interview/283-f9c5f122-e1ad-44b6-9fc9-6cba54558776)” encourages protestors to dress as frogs and dance in protest outside of the ICE facility. To support their efforts, an organization called [Operation Inflation](https://www.operationinflation.com/) is supplying free costumes to Portland protestors. 

I think it’s worth considering whether humorous efforts like these are an appropriate response to this scary, authoritarian time in American politics. 

This month, [ICE agents drove into](https://www.yahoo.com/news/articles/chicago-woman-dragged-her-car-201100192.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAK6UttxLL4jwWp2QfTLMGJIj3cFzp7Ytwz9-IAEAWhoGwSwJ_ZCeITvn_OxafXyPBDelTvF88MSXduxzekz5d-pGTc7J32u_j784jZqsVIcn9cz0CBBUCUKiCCdWknYy6CRwF2guIN_jk7SNiYjRA2qbay3p2TSOXYiP7zlphuTE) Dayanne Figueroa’s car, forced her door open, dragged her out by her legs and detained her. They later released her without charges.  In April, [ICE deported three](https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c4g8yj2n33yo) children — one of whom has Stage 4 cancer, all of whom are U.S. Citizens — to Honduras. In May, ICE agents [detained a Tufts University student](https://www.npr.org/2025/05/09/nx-s1-5393055/tufts-student-rumeysa-ozturk-ordered-freed-from-immigration-detention), Rümeysa Öztürk, in an “overcrowded mouse-infested cell with 23 other women” for six weeks in a move that was “likely to have been carried out solely in retaliation for an [op-ed she authored](https://www.tuftsdaily.com/article/2024/03/4ftk27sm6jkj) in her campus newspaper”. In October, ICE agents shoved a [photojournalist to the ground](https://www.the-independent.com/news/world/americas/us-politics/ice-federal-plaza-new-york-photographer-b2836898.html), sending him to the hospital with a head injury; and [shot a peacefully protesting pastor](https://www.yahoo.com/news/articles/ice-shot-praying-pastor-pepper-163526947.html) in the head with a pepper ball while he prayed. The Portland Frogs weren’t spared from this savagery. Just weeks ago, an ICE agent shot pepper spray [directly into the air vent](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UkLsIGoap7Y) of a protester's frog costume; leaving him trapped in a polyester bag, with only pepper spray to breathe. 

In short, ICE is an unaccountable, masked police force, used to enforce cruel policies. If all goes well, we will eventually hold the agents and administrators who carried out these atrocities accountable. Unfortunately, my sense is that there’s little political momentum towards this in Washington. The Portland protestors are a young movement – they definitely don’t have the collective power to push for this. Yet. But they’re making up for their lack of political clout with creativity. 

I believe the use of humor in Portland is a compelling method of protest for two reasons: it creates an eye-catching counternarrative, making it difficult to frame protestors as violent and it serves as a method of collective identity building. 

When asked about their motivations to protest, one masked frog said “[I’m out here protesting… especially in a frog costume, to show how ridiculous the notion that we are violent terrorists is.](https://x.com/NocontextMR/status/1976449998360551807)” Other protesters expressed similar sentiments, saying “[the best way to battle \[the Trump administration’s\] ridiculousness, is with more ridiculousness](https://www.instagram.com/reel/DP7SDwmibS2/?hl=en)”. 

According to UC Davis professor L.M. Bogad, this is a classic example of [tactical frivolity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tactical_frivolity) — the use of humor in public protest. In [an interview](https://www.themarshallproject.org/2025/10/22/trump-ice-portland-no-kings-protest) with The Marshall Project, he goes on to state that this tactic has a long history. It “goes back to carnival protests in the Middle Ages, where folks were saying very edgy things in public about the church or the king, but they had to do it in a way that made themselves absurd or silly so they could get away with it safely.” This technique has proven to be timeless; in Medieval times, as in Portland, protestors use humor as protective cover while delegitimizing authority. It’s hard for Trump and Noem to maintain their “war ravaged” claims against a backdrop of dancing costumes. 

In their absurd protest, Portlanders have also begun constructing a collective identity. Professor Cristina Flesher Fominaya identifies this as an important stage in building movements towards greater change, as the construction of collective identity are the “[processes that sustain movement groups between mobilizations, an active construct of the sense of "we-ness" which serves to invite participation and leads to action.](https://www.jstor.org/stable/26405492)” While this is true –– think about how the Portland Frog Brigades are a named movement, not just rag-tag anti-ICE protestors — I submit that this particular collective identity won’t spread outside of Oregon.  

Frog suits only work in a protest setting. Unlike the [pink, cat-eared hats](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pussyhat) of the Women's March, an inflatable frog suit doesn't immediately communicate what protestors oppose. Unlike a raised fist for [Black Power](https://www.rd.com/article/history-behind-the-clenched-first-and-the-symbol-for-black-power/), frog suits don’t communicate what protestors stand for. Costumes inevitably rely upon their backdrop – they create a powerful counternarrative when juxtaposed against brutal federal agents decked out in military gear. Removed from this context, they’re just silly costumes. 

This doesn’t mean that the Portland Frog Brigades isn’t an important movement. They’ve shown that humor can be a powerful symbol in the face of an authoritarian crackdown. Making tyranny look foolish in your hometown is the first step toward making it fall. But protestors will need to translate spectacle into sustained organizing to see real change. 

